To solve the heat equation for the image, we can use the finite difference method. Here's a MATLAB code to do that:

```MATLAB
% Parameters
width = 100;
height = 100;
intensity = 50;
time_period = 5;
step_size = 0.01;

% Initialize the image
image_initial = intensity * ones(height, width);

% Heat equation parameters
alpha = 1; % Diffusion coefficient
dx = 1;
dy = 1;
dt = step_size;
lambda_x = alpha * dt / dx^2;
lambda_y = alpha * dt / dy^2;

% Initialize the image after processing
image_final = image_initial;

% Time loop
for t = 0:dt:time_period
    % Spatial loop
    for i = 2:height-1
        for j = 2:width-1
            % Finite difference method
            image_final(i, j) = image_initial(i, j) + lambda_x * (image_initial(i+1, j) - 2 * image_initial(i, j) + image_initial(i-1, j)) + lambda_y * (image_initial(i, j+1) - 2 * image_initial(i, j) + image_initial(i, j-1));
        end
    end
    % Update the image
    image_initial = image_final;
end

% Display the images
figure;
subplot(1, 2, 1);
imshow(image_initial, []);
title('Before');

subplot(1, 2, 2);
imshow(image_final, []);
title('After');
```

This code initializes a 100 x 100 image with a constant intensity of 50. It then applies the heat equation using the finite difference method for a time period of 5 seconds with a step size of 0.01 seconds. Finally, it displays the before and after images side by side for comparison.
